SURGICAL PATHOLOGY REPORT - Final ___
DIAGNOSIS: MOST IN KEEPING WITH DIFFUSE LARGE B-CELL LYMPHOMA, 
SEE NOTE. 
Note: Sections show an enlarged lymph node with effacement of 
the normal nodal architecture by a vague nodular proliferation 
of atypical lymphocytes. The lymphocytes are predominantly large 
in size with round to slightly irregular nuclear contours, 
vesicular chromatin and single to multiple prominent nucleoli 
giving some cells a centroblastic appearance and some cells an 
immunoblastic appearance. Scattered smaller lymphocytes are 
present. Frequent apoptotic cells, tingible body macrophages and 
mitoses are seen. 

By immunohistochemistry, CD20 highlights the large lymphoma 
cells, which are negative for CD10 and CD5 and positive for 
MUM1. BCL6 highlights a subset of the lymphoma cells in nodular 
areas with variable dim to bright staining. BCL2 is diffusely 
positive. BCL1 is negative. CD3 and CD5 highlight scattered 
background T-cells with focal aggregates forming a nodular 
outline of the B-cells. CD21 and CD23 highlight disrupted and 
fragmented follicular dendritic cell meshwork. By Ki67 (MIB1) 
staining, the proliferation index is 70-80%. 

Concurrent cytogenetics showed a complex karyotype with gain of 
BCL2 and BCL6. There is no evidence of BCL2-IGH translocation 
and BCL6 or MYC rearrangement arguing against a double hit/ 
triple hit lymphoma (see separate report"___-___" for full 
result) 

Taken together, the morphologic and immunophenotypic features 
are in keeping with involvement by a large B-cell lymphoma. 
Although there is follicular dendritic cell meshwork's staining 
with CD21 and CD23 in the back ground, these meshworks are 
largely fragmented by large atypical B-cells that are not 
exclusively confined within these meshworks favoring a diffuse 
process. A concomitant peripheral blood clonal B- lymphocytosis 
was noted, however In the examined tissue there is no clear 
evidence of a small B-cell lymphoma component that support the 
possibility of secondary large B-cell transformation. Overall, 
it is best classified as diffuse large B cell lymphoma 
,non-germinal center type by the ___ algorithm. Correlation 
with clinical, cytogenetic (___-2410, CY19-7), flow cytometry 
(___) and laboratory findings is recommended.

caliber vessel. There is a 100% stenosis in the proximal 
segment. There are collaterals from the distal RCA.
RCA: The Right Coronary Artery, arising from the right cusp, is 
a large caliber vessel. There is a 95% stenosis in the proximal 
and mid segments. There is a 95% stenosis in the mid and distal 
segments. The Acute Marginal, arising from the proximal segment, 
is a small caliber vessel. The Right Posterior Descending 
Artery, arising from the distal segment, is a medium caliber 
vessel. The Right Posterolateral Artery, arising from the distal 
segment, is a medium caliber vessel.

Interventional Details
Percutaneous Coronary Intervention: Percutaneous coronary 
intervention (PCI) was performed on an ad hoc basis based on the 
coronary angiographic findings from the diagnostic portion of 
this procedure. A ___ AL 0.75 guiding catheter provided excellent 
support. After crossing with a wire all stenoses were dilated 
using a 2.0 mm NC balloon. Unsuccessful attempt to pass a 2.5mm 
x 38mm stent, so did further dilations using a 2.5mm NC balloon 
at high pressure. The balloon at this point became stuck to the 
wire
and pulled wire out of vessel as removed. Tried unsuccessfully 
to recross all stenoses using a Sion wire and then a Prowater 
wire but unsuccessful because of passage into dissection flaps.. 
Since there is only mild stenosis (approx 40%) and normal flow 
and patient free of chest pain, decided that risks outweigh 
benefits of more aggressive attempts.
Complications: There were no clinically significant 
complications.

Findings
 Three vessel coronary artery disease.
 PTCA alone (POBA) of RCA.
